To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

4 out of 5 stars
Sounds great for music and some additional features
Back when MP3 players first came out, there were only a few companies making them but now there are many in the market. The technology is common place but there are still some issues like sound quality and extra features to distinguish between the different choices.This Innioasis is a nice choice that sound great with plug-in headphones or Bluetooth sets. This is essentially an Android based system without the cell capability. As such, it handles Pandora, Amazon Music, as well as some obscure music services.It has a basic web browser but the big part is that the music sounds great and it is quick and responsive.There is a memory slot as well on the side to expend your memory to hold all your music files. The included earbuds are okay but not the best. I prefer to use my own instead.The interface is pretty basic but easy to navigate around in.The screen is a 4" LCD that is fairly sharp and bright. There are side buttons for volume and power on/off.It is charged by USB-C and seems to run for 5 to 6 hours if the screen is on.Overall, if you are looking for a dedicated music player that holds all your music and just works without issue, then this is a nice choice. It is solid and well build and comes with music-centric apps. You cannot add or uninstall them but it covers all the bases. For the price, this is a pretty solid winner.

Adopt, don't shop
5.0 out of 5 stars My first MP3 player
Reviewed in the United States on October 29, 2024
Color: PurpleAmazon Vine Customer Review of Free Product( What's this? )
I admit it. I am a Luddite. My spouse is the one that keeps up with technology and tells me when I need a new phone. He was one of the first to get an Ipod when they came out. I, on the other hand, just got a pair of wireless headphones. I wear them when I am working outside doing loud things, like running the chipper shredder or the leaf blower. I use the headphones paired with my Smartphone, but my spouse suggested getting an MP3 player because they are so versatile. I found this Innioasis music player and ordered it. The first thing I like about it is its compact size; it fits in my pocket better than my phone. It comes with a set of wired earbuds and a variety of ear pieces so you can get a good fit for your ears.

Now I haven't had this MP3 player long enough to be an expert on it, but I will tell you what I do know. There are two screens worth of shortcuts on this player. It comes with downloaded apps like Spotify, Amazon Music, and Pandora, which will require subscriptions. I happen to be an Amazon Prime member, so my understanding is that I get Amazon Music free, but I haven't figured out how to sign into it. You also have access to Kindle and Ebooks if you like to read. There is a shortcut for FM radio if you have stations that you like listening to. There is a clock function, a calculator, a timer, and a stopwatch.

Like I said before, I am a Luddite, so it is going to take a while before I get familiar with all of the functions that this MP3 player performs. I have gone into Spotify for free to see how the music sounds using the earbuds. The sound quality coming from the earbuds is great. My next task is to see if I can get my wireless headphones to pair with the MP3 player. I think my spouse is going to have to help me with that.

4.0 out of 5 stars Fine audio and video player for the price
Reviewed in the United States on October 31, 2024
Color: PurpleVerified Purchase
This player almost has the functionality of a cellphone, except, of course, a cellular modem and camera and browser and apps. It comes with a custom version of Android OS and loaded with media software, FM radio and utilities. In my case, I listen to Pandora in offline mode while I run. The player has a micro SD slot you can use for importing music or saving media. Sound quality from the speaker is adequate and earbuds are provided for stereo listening. The earbud leads are the FM radio antenna. You can pair Bluetooth earbuds for wireless listening (other than FM). Battery life is OK, but seems a bit short to me unless I turn screen brightness down and shut off WiFi. The main downsides I see are that the unit is quite heavy and that I imagine dropping it might cause substantial damage. Probably worth it to find a gel case that fits. For those reasons I deducted 1 star.

xiali
5.0 out of 5 stars Nice design,Works great
Reviewed in the United States on November 4, 2024
Color: Glacier-BlueAmazon Vine Customer Review of Free Product( What's this? )
This MP3 Player is a fantastic product, with a beautiful design and a satisfying weight in hand that adds a premium feel to it. It feels almost like an Android smartphone without the communication features or internet, reminding me of the iPod Touch from years agoa touch of nostalgia I appreciate.

I love the powerful functionality of this device. Not only does it support local music playback, but it also comes with pre-installed streaming apps like Spotify, Pandora, and Amazon Music. Streaming over WiFi opens up a wide variety of audio content, and I tested Amazon Music, it worked flawlessly.

The 4-inch touch screen is a great size. easy to hold and just right for viewing details without being overly bulky. The screen is sharp and responsive, making navigation feel as natural as using a smartphone.

The built-in speaker delivers clear audio, which, while not exceptional, is sufficient for casual listening. It also offers other features beyond music playback, including recording, adding more entertainment options.

The MP3 player comes with a quality pair of wired earphones that double as an FM antennaa very practical touch. I appreciate that, as it enables FM radio functionality, which is surprisingly handy. Bluetooth 4.2, though not the latest, performs well with clear, crisp sound, stable connectivity, and zero delays.

One minor thing that caught me off guard: the product title on the webpage lists it as a 160GB MP3 Player. Initially, I thought it had 160GB of internal storage, but it actually includes 32GB internal storage plus a 128GB SD card. It still offers 160GB in total, but this distinction might be a bit confusing for some users like me. Overall, its a fantastic, versatile device that delivers on its promises.

KH
4.0 out of 5 stars Great music player with good quality playback.
Reviewed in Canada on October 28, 2024
Color: PurpleAmazon Vine Customer Review of Free Product( What's this? )
This is a great music player, good quality playback in both wired and wireless modes, and a decent 3.5mm jack that outputs enough power to run 300 ohm headphones.

This music player supports all main file types, including FLAC, OGG, MP3, etc. The built in music player for this device is the HiBy Music player, which has the basic functionalities of playback, library management, sorting by album, and equalizer settings. However, I personally found the entire UI clunky and unintuitive to use - for example, to delete a song from the device that is currently playing, I would have to go to the album list or a list of all the songs in the device, hold on the music, and then press delete. On many other music apps, there is simply a choice to delete it on the "Now Playing" screen. However, since you can install your own apps, this isn't a massive issue.

Now let's talk about hardware. While I can't identify the type of processor, the available RAM is 2GB.
The device has 32 GB of built in storage and comes with an unbranded 128 GB MicroSD card, which altogether add up to 160 GB total. The SD card can be inserted via a slot on the outside of the phone and hasn't failed yet, which is great. I was able to transfer 32 GB worth of files to it without any interruptions. The hardware is more than enough for the device to run smoothly and has plenty of storage as well.

The 3.5 mm jack is too loud in my opinion though. At minimum volume, with the included earphones (the included earphones are surprisingly decent, with good resolution and sound quality) it feels like it borders on hearing damage levels. It is also easily able to drive my HD600 headphones, which have an impedance of 300 ohms, well above hearing damage levels. Bluetooth is fine though, especially if you enable absolute volume in developer mode (this allows the volume control of your Bluetooth device and the music player to function independently of each other).

Bluetooth connectivity is flawless. I have yet to have a disconnect or any distortion issues. It supports LDAC and AptX lossless as well, though only has AVRCP 1.4.

Build quality is nothing to complain about. The physical buttons for volume and power are snug in their sockets, and the chassis is made of a combination of plastic and metal. The screen isn't anything special, though it does come with a thin pre-installed screen protector.

Overall, it's a good music player. With decent build quality, an amplified 3.5 mm jack, and Bluetooth connectivity, it has nearly everything you would want from a basic music player. However, there is of course a value proposition to be made: you could get this music player, but you could also get an old phone with a headphone jack for less. The phone would have a larger screen. Either way, if your final goal is to have a good music player, you can't go wrong with either choice.

4.0 out of 5 stars A good quality MP3 Player
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on October 30, 2024
Color: GreenAmazon Vine Customer Review of Free Product( What's this? )
I mainly purchased this MP3 player for using at the gym. The WIFI reception there is a bit hit and miss so this allows me to download a lot more of my music than I want to add to my phone.

The first thing you notice when switching on is the number of preinstalled apps. There are several music apps such as Apple, Spotify and Amazon Music. There are also lots of e-readers, such as Kindle and eBook. As I have Spotify and Amazon Music on my phone I do not have any need for these. I think the screen is a bit small to read a book on so I won't be using any of the e-readers. I will delete all the apps that I won't use to free up a bit of space and make the opening screen less cluttered.
I may try the audio book apps so will keep these for now.

The FM Radio has worked well so far. You need to use plug in headphones for the radio to work, a set is included. It is easy to tune the radio in and it automatically stores the stations. Any favourite stations are shown on the main radio screen.

Music is easily loaded onto the player and accessed through the Music app. Here you can view your music by Title, Album or Artist.

I found the MP3 player quickly connects to my internet and Bluetooth speakers. It is also easy to use in the car with an auxiliary cable.

I can't see me using this MP3 player to access any apps where I need WIFI as I may as well use my phone, but it has a good amount of storage space due to the micro SD card to store plenty of music to listen to when at the gym or out and about, which is why I ordered it.

I can't see me using this MP3 player to access any apps where I need WIFI as I may as well use my phone, but it has a good amount of storage space due to the micro SD card to store plenty of music to listen to when at the gym or out and about, which is why I ordered it.
